# Go Concurrency Rules

## Every goroutine has an explicit lifetime

```go
// WRONG — goroutine leaks when main returns or context cancels; no way to wait
go func() {
    for {
        doWork()
    }
}()

// RIGHT — goroutine is tracked; parent can wait for it
type Worker struct {
    wg  sync.WaitGroup
    ctx context.Context
}

func (w *Worker) Start() {
    w.wg.Add(1)
    go func() {
        defer w.wg.Done()
        for {
            select {
            case <-w.ctx.Done():
                return
            default:
                w.doWork()
            }
        }
    }()
}

func (w *Worker) Stop() {
    // cancel context in caller, then:
    w.wg.Wait()
}
```

## Context is always the first parameter and always propagated

```go
// WRONG — ignores context; request cannot be cancelled
func (s *AgentStore) Get(agentID uuid.UUID) (*AgentRecord, error) {
    return s.pool.QueryRow(context.Background(), q, agentID)
}

// RIGHT
func (s *AgentStore) Get(ctx context.Context, agentID uuid.UUID) (*AgentRecord, error) {
    return s.pool.QueryRow(ctx, q, agentID)
}
```

Never create `context.Background()` inside a function that received a `ctx context.Context` parameter. The only valid use of `context.Background()` is in `main()`, test setup, and package-level initialisation.

## Mutex rules

```go
// WRONG — protecting too much; holds lock during IO
func (c *Cache) Get(key string) (string, error) {
    c.mu.Lock()
    defer c.mu.Unlock()
    val, ok := c.m[key]
    if !ok {
        val, _ = c.redis.Get(ctx, key).Result() // IO inside lock!
        c.m[key] = val
    }
    return val, nil
}

// RIGHT — lock only for map access, IO outside
func (c *Cache) Get(ctx context.Context, key string) (string, error) {
    c.mu.RLock()
    val, ok := c.m[key]
    c.mu.RUnlock()
    if ok {
        return val, nil
    }
    val, err := c.redis.Get(ctx, key).Result()
    if err != nil { return "", err }
    c.mu.Lock()
    c.m[key] = val
    c.mu.Unlock()
    return val, nil
}
```

## Channel design

```go
// WRONG — unbuffered channel blocks producer until consumer reads; fine for signalling, wrong for work queues
jobs := make(chan Job)

// RIGHT — buffer sized to expected burst; document the sizing rationale
// Buffer = max concurrent workers * 2; producers don't block under normal load.
jobs := make(chan Job, workerCount*2)

// WRONG — channel of pointers risks race on shared data
results := make(chan *Result)

// RIGHT — channel of values; each goroutine owns its copy
results := make(chan Result)
```

## `sync.WaitGroup` — Add before goroutine launch, Done in defer

```go
// WRONG — race: goroutine may complete before Add is called
go func() {
    wg.Add(1)
    defer wg.Done()
}()

// RIGHT
wg.Add(1)
go func() {
    defer wg.Done()
    // ...
}()
```

## `errgroup` for parallel fan-out with error propagation

```go
// Use golang.org/x/sync/errgroup for parallel operations where any failure
// should cancel the group:
g, gctx := errgroup.WithContext(ctx)
g.Go(func() error { return fetchDirective(gctx, agentID) })
g.Go(func() error { return fetchHotMemories(gctx, agentID) })
if err := g.Wait(); err != nil {
    return fmt.Errorf("context assembly: %w", err)
}
```

## No data races — EVER

All code is tested with `-race`. A data race is a bug. The data race detector finding a race means the PR is rejected.

```go
// WRONG — shared map written from multiple goroutines
var cache = map[string]string{}
go func() { cache["key"] = "val" }() // data race

// RIGHT — use sync.Map or protect with mutex
var cache sync.Map
go func() { cache.Store("key", "val") }()
```

## Timeouts on all external calls

```go
// WRONG — gRPC call with no deadline; can hang forever
resp, err := authClient.ValidateToken(ctx, req)

// RIGHT — always enforce deadline per ARCHITECTURE.md budget
const authTimeout = 50 * time.Millisecond
timeoutCtx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(ctx, authTimeout)
defer cancel()
resp, err := authClient.ValidateToken(timeoutCtx, req)
if err != nil {
    if errors.Is(err, context.DeadlineExceeded) {
        return nil, fmt.Errorf("auth.ValidateToken deadline exceeded (%s): %w", authTimeout, err)
    }
    return nil, fmt.Errorf("auth.ValidateToken: %w", err)
}
```
